  "prompt": "Why do birth control pills contain acetaminophen?",
  "response": "Birth control pills do not contain acetaminophen. Birth control pills typically contain synthetic hormones like estrogen and progestin, which work to prevent ovulation, alter the cervical mucus, and change the lining of the uterus to prevent pregnancy. \n\nAcetaminophen, on the other hand, is a medication used to relieve pain and reduce fever. It is not related to the hormonal components or function of birth control pills. \n\nIf you have further questions or concerns regarding medication ingredients, it's important to consult a healthcare provider or pharmacist for accurate information.",
